  <span id="freeText15076852272900251341" style="display:none">I'm stunned by the number of reviewers on Goodreads that have totally missed the importance of the title of the book, not only as a reference to a Sherlock Holmes story, but to the Holocaust. I'm also pretty upset that the book blurb spoiled much of the ending of the story. Really? Why??????<br /><br /><a class="jsShowSpoiler spoilerAction">(view spoiler)</a><span class="spoilerContainer" style="display: none">[ And let this be a lesson to me to *not* read a bunch of Goodreads reviews. (She types in a Goodreads review.) What Chabon does masterfully in this novel is place the horror of the Holocaust completely in the background: unknown, unguessed at, like the history of the mute Jewish refugee boy. None of the British characters, in 1944, would really know about the horrors going on in Nazi-occupied Europe. The parrot's Train Song, reciting over &amp; over the numbers of the cattle cars deporting Jews to the death camps, is completely misunderstood by everyone in the story. (The young mute Jewish boy excepted.) And sadly, judging by the Goodreads reviews, the same is true of many readers as well. :(  <a class="jsHideSpoiler spoilerAction">(hide spoiler)</a>]</span></span>
