    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_1714595720" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1714595720" />
    <a title="Georgie-who-is-Sarah-Drew" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/9572229-georgie-who-is-sarah-drew"><img alt="Georgie-who-is-Sarah-Drew" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1623778605p2/9572229.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1714595720?book_show_action=true">Jul 31, 2016</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Georgie-who-is-Sarah-Drew" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Georgie-who-is-Sarah-Drew" href="/user/show/9572229-georgie-who-is-sarah-drew">Georgie-who-is-Sarah-Drew</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Kindle Edition " href="/book/show/18972949-the-final-solution">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/9572229-georgie-who-is-sarah-drew?shelf=stars-4-5">stars-4-5</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/9572229-georgie-who-is-sarah-drew?shelf=tag-reviewed">tag-reviewed</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/9572229-georgie-who-is-sarah-drew?shelf=archived">archived</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/9572229-georgie-who-is-sarah-drew?shelf=genre-tec">genre-tec</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/9572229-georgie-who-is-sarah-drew?shelf=fiction">fiction</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1714595720" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer155380672012011582">A very rewarding and beautifully-written book. There&apos;s a beginning, middle and end - but the plot&apos;s sufficiently ambiguous to allow for your own interpretation. And note that Chabon carefully calls this A Story of Detection, <u>not</u> A Detective Story: for all there&apos;s a murder, it&apos;s the least important part of the story. <br/><br/>When, in 1944, an elderly bee-keeping Sherlock Holmes is drawn into a Murder at the Vicarage, he&apos;s less interested in the murder than in the simultaneous disappearance of a singularl</span>
  <span id="freeText155380672012011582" style="display:none">A very rewarding and beautifully-written book. There's a beginning, middle and end - but the plot's sufficiently ambiguous to allow for your own interpretation. And note that Chabon carefully calls this A Story of Detection, <u>not</u> A Detective Story: for all there's a murder, it's the least important part of the story. <br /><br />When, in 1944, an elderly bee-keeping Sherlock Holmes is drawn into a Murder at the Vicarage, he's less interested in the murder than in the simultaneous disappearance of a singularly intelligent and loquacious African Grey parrot belonging to Linus, a young Jewish refugee. The murder is solved, but the real interest is in Chabon's wry and dispassionate dissection of the cast. Almost every character has POV time: it's a way of keeping the reader non-judgemental, and as distanced as Chabon - or a Holmes. The rural setting and the slightly acid tone are a bit <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/author/show/104015.Barbara_Pym" title="Barbara Pym" rel="nofollow noopener">Barbara Pym</a>-y: nice.<br /><br />Having said that, quite a lot of the book is in Holmes' POV. I've read a couple of homages to Holmes this year (both the schlocky <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/25687822.Compound_a_Felony_A_Queer_Affair_of_Sherlock_Holmes" title="Compound a Felony A Queer Affair of Sherlock Holmes by Elinor Gray" rel="nofollow noopener">Compound a Felony: A Queer Affair of Sherlock Holmes</a> and the superior <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/28588390.A_Study_in_Scarlet_Women__Lady_Sherlock___1_" title="A Study in Scarlet Women (Lady Sherlock, #1) by Sherry Thomas" rel="nofollow noopener">A Study in Scarlet Women</a>). Neither of them were half as convincing as this portrayal (I imagine Holmes looking like a gaunter version of Prince Philip, only with much less patience for garden parties and warm sandwiches). Although he's never referred to by name, he <u>is</u> Holmes and he's lost nothing of his acerbic nature over the years:-<br /><i>He was aware of the existence of a vocabulary for the consolation of sorrowing children, but it was one he had never troubled to learn.</i> <br />or<br /><i>"Do they ever sting you?" the man from London said.<br />"Constantly."<br />"Does it hurt?"<br />The old man raised the netting, so that he would not have to waste a perfectly good yes on such a fatuous question. The man from London concealed the traces of a smile in his graying blond mustache.<br />"Suppose it would," he said. "Like honey, do you?"<br />"Not particularly, no," said the old man.<br />The man from London appeared to be a little surprised by this reply, then nodded and confessed that he was not terribly fond of honey himself.<br />"Know who I am?" he said, after a moment.<br />"Genus and species," the old man said.</i><br /><br />The title works on a number of levels - it's a clear nod to Doyle's <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/4702372.The_Adventure_of_the_Final_Problem__The_Memoirs_of_Sherlock_Holmes___11_" title="The Adventure of the Final Problem (The Memoirs of Sherlock Holmes, #11) by Arthur Conan Doyle" rel="nofollow noopener">The Adventure of the Final Problem</a>, in which Holmes "dies". And while this isn't a morbid book, the old man is keenly aware of the possibility of death at every turn<br /><i>While he crawled on hands and knees the possibility of his dying thus recurred to him, and he found to his pleasure that no shadow of indignity darkened the prospect. Long life wore away everything that was not essential. Some old men finished their lives as little more than the sum total of their memories, others as nothing but a pair of grasping pincers, or a set of bitter axioms proven. It would please him well enough to amount to no more in the end than a single great organ of detection, reaching into blankness for a clue.</i><br /><br />There are also several references to Hitler's Final Solution, <a class="jsShowSpoiler spoilerAction">(view spoiler)</a><span class="spoilerContainer" style="display: none">[including a desperately sad explanation of the mysterious strings of numbers Bruno the parrot has memorised <a class="jsHideSpoiler spoilerAction">(hide spoiler)</a>]</span>. But for a book that deals in murder, genocide and imminent death, it's drily entertaining throughout. <br /><i>Men, policemen in particular, tended to discount the capacity of animals to enact, often with considerable panache, the foulest of crimes and the most daring stunts.</i><br /><br />Chabon's a stylist - I loved his description of the old man's hives just before he collects all the honey: <br /><i>The hive gave off an air of doomed contentment, like a city sleeping it off on the day after carnival, contemplated from a hilltop by an army of Huns.</i> <br />It's perhaps a good thing though that this is not a long read, as I think I might grow a little weary of the unremittingly stylised writing. Appreciative, but perhaps wishing that not <u>everything</u> got the treatment - <i>the car [had] slitted blackout headlights that echoed the sun-blasted squint of its passenger.</i><br /><br />But this was a tartly intelligent book. Glad I read it.<br /><br /><br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="155380672012011582" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


