  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_4038819728" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/4038819728" />
    <a title="Joe Kraus" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/2422229-joe-kraus"><img alt="Joe Kraus" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1470757957p2/2422229.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/4038819728?book_show_action=true">Jun 03, 2021</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Joe Kraus" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Joe Kraus" href="/user/show/2422229-joe-kraus">Joe Kraus</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/2422229-joe-kraus?shelf=jewish-american">jewish-american</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer4038819728" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer14965461601335958751">Michael Chabon doesn’t seem to look at the Holocaust straight-on.<br/><br/>I sympathize. The horrors of what our parents’ generation went through are overwhelming. I am grateful for those who, staring straight at it, can do the crucial history and reflection to keep the experience in the American and world conversation. <br/><br/>So Chabon, like me in a much less accomplished way, looks at the echoes and shadows of the experience rather than the full evil of the experience itself.<br/><br/>As such, this one hardly feels like</span>
  <span id="freeText14965461601335958751" style="display:none">Michael Chabon doesn’t seem to look at the Holocaust straight-on.<br /><br />I sympathize. The horrors of what our parents’ generation went through are overwhelming. I am grateful for those who, staring straight at it, can do the crucial history and reflection to keep the experience in the American and world conversation. <br /><br />So Chabon, like me in a much less accomplished way, looks at the echoes and shadows of the experience rather than the full evil of the experience itself.<br /><br />As such, this one hardly feels like a Holocaust novel at all. A young teenage boy, who’s mute after his experience in the early years of WWII, has his parrot stolen. Someone might have taken it because of its intrinsic value. Or, more disturbingly, someone may have taken it because it has memorized a series of numbers that might reveal a crucial Nazi code.<br /><br />Short as this is, I have to reveal a SPOILER that didn’t surprise me in the least. Those numbers, “the final solution” to this part of the mystery, reflect that other awful final solution. They are most likely the numbers on the train cars carrying Jews to Auschwitz and other death camps. (Or, less likely but still suggested, they are the numbers tattooed on the wrists of Jews.)<br /><br />In other words, this is a novel – or, more properly, a novella – meditating on the horror of the Holocaust from the corner of our various narrators’ perspectives. Make no mistake: when you strip away the sometimes silly distractions of the plot, this is about the central horror of the 20th Century.<br /><br />I acknowledge the power of that, and I have found myself chewing over the cleverness and insight of the literary experiment. This is something worth doing. It lacks the fundamental what-if humor and mourning of The Yiddish Policeman’s Union (one of the most enjoyable novels of the last couple decades), and it lacks the endless creativity (if flawed ending) of The Amazing Adventures of Cavalier and Klay. Even so, it’s one more notch on Chabon’s impressive belt.<br /><br />All that said, the “distractions of the plot” strike me as weaker than they might have been. What we get is a kind of ‘cozy,’ a murder mystery featuring a kind of aged Mr. Marple who’d rather tend to his bees than settle into another murder investigation. We get as well a sudden murder of a secondary character. That comes across differently in Agatha Christie; here it’s a troubling reminder of the millions of deaths taking place elsewhere in the same moment. That’s not all bad – it’s yet another side-door into reflecting on the Holocaust – but it seems clumsy.<br /><br />There’s also a strange effect in the way this switches narrators. I’m not entirely turned off by it, but it seems another somewhat clumsy way to reinvent narrative perspective.<br /><br />So, I’m glad I read this one, and I’m glad to revisit Chabon’s work after a few years away from it. I’ll keep thinking about what I see as the heart of its reflection on the Holocaust, but I suspect I’ll forget the material around it fairly soon.<br /><br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="14965461601335958751" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


